text:
(In reply to Matthias Andree from comment #11)

I should finally have access to big endian environments (powerpc64 and powerpc) later this month, at least for a time. That will allow a direct test of the type conversions without little endian byte ordering being the implicit context.


The original context was:

promoted type 'int' of K&R function parameter is not compatible with the parameter type 'db_indx_t' (aka 'unsigned short')


Your code did not use an unsigned type for the parameter:

long f(i)
    short int i;
{
    printf("in f: i=%hd (as long: i=%ld)\n", i, (long)i);
    return i;
}


I changed to unsigned parameter(s) but left the rest alone (other than having 2 such arguments and 2 printf's because I was curious). It might have been better if I'd adjusted the format as well.

But:

long f(unsigned short int i, unsigned short int j);

long f(i,j)
    unsigned short int i;
    unsigned short int j;
{
    printf("in f: i=%hd (as long: i=%ld)\n", i, (long)i);
    printf("in f: j=%hd (as long: j=%ld)\n", j, (long)j);
    return i;
}

for:

    long n = f(-17,40000);

returns 65519 from f (into n), which is not mathematically value preserving of the argument value -17, even for little endian when the return type (a conversion type) is signed but larger than the arguments. This illustrates that the width and signed status changes can matter for even little endian and that the details of item_space and item_size have the potential lead to problems if the argument expressions wrap. (I've not analyzed the code details in those routines.)

The same would have resulted from "int f(i,j)" and "int f(unsigned short int i, unsigned short int j)" when int is 32 bits or more and short is 16 bits.
